\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Overall Performance}
\label{sec:overall-pass}

\begin{table*}[t]
\centering
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json, quantitative_findings_gpt54.json > canonical > failure_taxonomy
\caption{Overall pass rates. \qwenshort{} covers 626 valid records (426 L0 + 200 ablation) after excluding 82 records involving 9 \knownfail{} specs. \gptnew{} covers 822 valid records (426 L0 + 396 ablation); \knownfail{} specs were pre-excluded from the evaluation batch.}
\label{tab:overall-pass}
\small
\resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{%
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrrrl@{}}
\toprule
Model & \pass{} & \buildfail{} & \runfail{} & \verifyfail{} & \extractionfail{} & Total & Rate [95\% Wilson CI] \\
\midrule
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > failure_taxonomy > status_counts
\qwen{} & 230 & 245 & 121 & 29 & 1 & 626 & 36.7\% [33.1\%, 40.6\%] \\
% src: quantitative_findings_gpt54.json > canonical > failure_taxonomy > status_counts (all 822 valid records)
\gptnew{} & 621 & 123 & 43 & 32 & 3 & 822 & 75.5\% [72.5\%, 78.4\%] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}%
}
\end{table*}
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > aggregate_pass_rates > overall: value=0.3674, ci=[0.3306, 0.4059], n=626
Kernel-centric evaluation isolates executable kernel translation from repository reconstruction. \qwenshort{} passes 230 of 626 valid records, or 36.7\%~[33.1\%, 40.6\%], across five benchmark suites, ten translation directions, and five augmentation levels (Table~\ref{tab:overall-pass}).
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > aggregate_pass_rates > per_suite
Per-suite rates range from 65.2\% (HeCBench, $n{=}184$) through 28.2\% (Rodinia, $n{=}380$) and 9.1\% (mixbench, $n{=}22$) to 4.6\% (XSBench, $n{=}22$) and 0\% (RSBench, $n{=}18$), reflecting the heterogeneous difficulty of the curated corpus.

The comparison to repository-level work is the main methodological point. ParEval-Repo reports 0\% pass@1 for all tested models on repository-level applications larger than 133~SLoC~\cite{ParEvalRepo2025}.
% src: sloc_analysis.json: 27 of 31 evaluated kernels above ParEval-Repo 133 SLoC threshold
Of the 31 evaluated kernels, 27 (87\%) exceed that threshold (Section~\ref{sec:benchmark-curation}), but \parbench{} fixes host code, build infrastructure, and I/O, isolating kernel translation from repository reconstruction. Under this isolation, \qwenshort{} achieves 36.7\% overall and 40.3\%~[29.7\%, 51.8\%] on CUDA-to-OpenMP at L0.
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > direction_pass_rates > standard > cuda-to-omp: value=0.4028, ci=[0.2972, 0.5182], n=72
This does not make the task easy; it separates kernel translation failures from full-repository reconstruction failures.

\subsection{pass@$k$ Analysis}
\label{sec:passk-analysis}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{pass@$k$ results for \qwenshort{} (L0 only, temperature~0.7, three independent samples per task, 142 unique source-target pairs). CIs are normal-approximation intervals on the macro-averaged Chen et al.\ estimator, not Wilson intervals on binomial counts.}
\label{tab:pass-at-k-main}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lr@{}}
\toprule
Metric & Value [95\% CI] \\
\midrule
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > pass_at_k > pass_at_1: value=0.2394, ci=[0.1791, 0.2998], n=142
pass@1 & 23.9\% [17.9\%, 30.0\%] \\
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > pass_at_k > pass_at_3: value=0.3521, ci=[0.2733, 0.4310], n=142
pass@3 & 35.2\% [27.3\%, 43.1\%] \\
\midrule
% src: quantitative_findings_qwen.json > canonical > pass_at_k > task_classification
Always pass (3/3) & 19 tasks (13.4\%) \\
Noisy (1--2/3) & 31 tasks (21.8\%) \\
Hard fail (0/3) & 92 tasks (64.8\%) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The 36.7\% per-record rate in Table~\ref{tab:overall-pass} treats each sample and augmentation level independently. The pass@$k$ analysis below restricts to the 142 L0 tasks and macro-averages to estimate single-sample and three-sample success probabilities. Each of the 142 tasks generates three independent samples at temperature~0.7, yielding 426 L0 records that contribute to the per-record rate.

Additional stochastic samples partially recover only 31 of 142 tasks and none of the 92 hard failures. Of 142 unique L0 source-target pairs, 92 (64.8\%) produce no passing sample across three independent attempts (Table~\ref{tab:pass-at-k-main}). Only 19 tasks (13.4\%) pass in all three samples, while the remaining 31 (21.8\%) are noisy and are passing in some samples but not others. The gap between pass@1 (23.9\%) and pass@3 (35.2\%) is modest; additional samples yield diminishing returns. Limited stochastic resampling is insufficient to recover most task-direction pairs.

\subsection{Direction Dependence}
\label{sec:direction-analysis}

\begin{table*}[t]
\centering
